lign": "start", "boxShadow": "none", "backgroundImage": "none"}, "htmlRect": {"x": 0, "y": 0, "width": 1440, "height": 1939.5, "bottom": 1939.5, "right": 1440, "area": 2792880}, "visibleText": "Ink & Insomnia journal essays reading-list about contact Essays Longer pieces, written slowly, mostly between midnight and four. On Rereading Sebald in Winter 3,420 words Returning to The Rings of Saturn after a decade, I find the fog has not lifted \u2014 only the reader has changed shape inside it. The Quiet Violence of Open-Plan Offices 2,815 words A meditation on the architecture of forced visibility, and what eight years of shared desks taught me about silence as a private resource. What Insomnia Teaches 4,102 words After three winters of broken sleep, I stopped fighting the dark hours and started taking notes \u2014 this is what they said back. Notes from a Former Librarian 2,260 words On leaving the stacks for freelance copywriting, and the small grief of no longer being paid to know where things belong. Montr\u00e9al in the Off-Season 3,005 words Between the festivals and the slush, there is a city that belongs to people who walk slowly \u2014 and to the d\u00e9panneurs that stay open past two. Against the Productive Morning 1,940 words A defense of the late hours for those whose best sentences refuse to arrive before the streetlights do. Translation as a Form of Patience 3,580 words What I learned about my own language by spending two years trying, and mostly failing, to carry Ernaux into English in my notebook. Ink & Insomnia \u2014 written from Montr\u00e9al by Mara Sol\u00e8ne. For correspondence, see contact ."}